On which interface?
Done

Why would a user use this value?  You list a lot of things for code (like getState), but don't really relate them to redfish, the behavior, the user-api, or why it needs to exist.  Can you take another attempt at this?  Reading through the patchset, I don't really understand why we want anything but "enabled" supported.

Hi Ed,

My thinking was that we could add some more granular info regarding the sensors.  I didn't make sense to me that a sensor would be considered "Enabled" when it's reading null because it requires host power.  But if "Enabled" is what we want then I can delete this patchset.

> I didn't make sense to me that a sensor would be considered "Enabled" when it's reading null because it requires host power.

The above isn't captured in your commit message.  I wasn't saying we don't want this, but "Redfish Sensors should read unavailable if the reading is null, and that difference is useful to the user." is much more clear than what's in the commit message now.  It references what we're changing, and why a user cares.

Also, we should double check with DMTF that the intent is for sensors to go unavailable if the status is null.  I forget what the intent was there.
I posted this question on the redfishforum (https://redfishforum.com/thread/991/sensor-state-value-when-reading), and it would make sense to have the State be more tied to the sensor reading values.
What system/sensor are you testing on?  I suspect this line can be removed.
Done
Redfish tests?
Done
Any progress here?
Any progress here?

Hi Ed, 

Checking with some folks about the schema for the Resource State.
Why does this need to be a default parameter?  Generally this isn't how we would model this.  We would parse out the interfaces in the dbus scope, then pass down the parsed values.
I had this so it would work with the getState used for power supplies that don't have any DBusPropertiesMap in its scope.  I've changed it now.
Unpacking needs to be done in the scope above, and avoid passing the direct raw dbus dicts through too many layers.
Do you mean in the objectPropertiesToJson function?  The getHealth does something similar.
Minor things to fix here, but commit message is looking much better.
nit, please just call this "available" to match the property name.
Done
Done

Can we move this example over to using the generated enumerations?  I realize it's not really related to the patch, but the typesafe interfaces prevent typos on enums like this.  It should be pretty trivial to add.

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/5ae1f7f3e0c78f84d153f7ef24ee22bb1c73eaa0/redfish-core/include/generated/enums/resource.hpp#L8
Done
Why this over UnavailableOffline which I feel matches better with the D-Bus property?
I was debating between "StandbyOffline" and "UnavailableOffline", so I have no issue changing it.
I added an extra check to the checkAvailable pointer, but I don't think we'd want to return because there's stuff below like getHealth() that we'd want to do still.
If you want to rearrange it so that the code after this block still runs on a parse failure, feel free, but internal error needs to be set on dbus interfaces that don't match what we expect.

What you did wasn't quite what I was thinking (state is still getting populated with a potentially wrong value on error) but at least an error is getting set.

Looks good enough for me.
Would "else if (checkAvailable != nullptr)" be better because success would have to be true?

no, because in theory that parameter could've been omitted on purpose.

I'm mostly commenting that if we set 500, we technically don't KNOW what Status/State should've been, because we didn't get all the data for it.


All good, patchset is fine as is.
